Call on Microsoft to allow online freedom

Microsoft is aiding the repression of freedom of expression and=20
information in China by complying with Chinese Government requests=20
that result in censorship of the internet.

It filters the results of politically-sensitive searches and=20
removes blogs critical of the Chinese Government. This censorship=20
contradicts the very principles and values that Microsoft was=20
founded upon.

Urge Microsoft to abide by human rights principles today
http://action.amnesty.org.au/centre/action/14023/?utm_source=3Dnewsletter=
&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_content=3D09Jul2008

Celebrate leadership during NAIDOC

We're encouraging supporters to join in celebrating Aboriginal and=20
Torres Strait Islander leadership and culture during NAIDOC week=20
(6=E2=80=9313 July). It's also a time to urge the Australian Government t=
o=20
reduce the 17-year life expectancy gap by providing the health,=20
education and housing services so many of us take for granted.

To find out what is happening in your area contact your local=20
Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander group or check the NAIDOC=20
website.

For a list of activities taking place click here
http://www.naidoc.org.au/08_events.aspx?utm_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_mediu=
m=3Demail&utm_content=3D09Jul2008

Give a voice to 4.7 million Iraqi refugees

Post the US-led invasion, escalating violence has resulted in=20
millions of innocent people fleeing their homes to avoid kidnapping,=20
blackmail, rape, torture or death.

Read our recent report on the plight of Iraq's refugees.
http://action.amnesty.org.au/refugees/comments/14371/?utm_source=3Dnewsle=
tter&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_content=3D09Jul2008

Help us demand that governments take responsibility for the crisis=20
and tell the international community that inaction is no longer an=20
option.

Support Amnesty International's work today
https://www.amnesty.org.au/donate?utm_source=3Daction&utm_medium=3Dget+in=
volved?utm_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_content=3D09Jul2008=


Letters of thanks

Amnesty International has received letters from two prisoners we=20
have worked with to thank our members and activists for their=20
support.

Recently-released Guant=C3=A1namo Bay detainee Sami al-Hajj wrote to=20
thank everyone who wrote letters to him. He received 10,000 letters=20
while in detention and says he will never forget their help. Read=20
his reply.
http://action.amnesty.org.au/hrs/comments/14687/?utm_source=3Dnewsletter&=
utm_medium=3Demail&utm_content=3D09Jul2008

Chinese human rights defender Zeng Jinyan, wife of recently jailed=20
activist Hu Jia, also wrote to express her deep thanks and=20
gratitude for all the letters of support she has received since her=20
husband's imprisonment, which help her realise she is not alone=20
through her ongoing house arrest.

Read Zeng Jinyan's letter
http://uncensor.com.au/uncensor/blog/your_letters_make_a_difference/?utm_=
source=3Dnewsletter&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_content=3D09Jul2008

